# Branch Workflow and Protection Rules

## Never work directly on main

- **Do not make commits or edits on `main`** for any change. Always work on a branch.
- **Before starting any new work**: create and checkout a new branch from `main`, then make changes. This applies to all change types: features, fixes, chores, docs, refactors, tests, CI/build, perf, etc.
- **AI assistants**: when the user asks for any new change, create a branch first using a name that matches the conventional commit type (e.g. `feat/short-name`, `fix/short-name`, `chore/short-name`, `docs/short-name`, `refactor/short-name`, `test/short-name`, `ci/short-name`, `build/short-name`, `perf/short-name`), then implement. Do not commit or push to `main`.

## Development Workflow

1. **Create a branch from `main` first** (or fork and branch): `git checkout main && git pull && git checkout -b <type>/short-name` — use the type that matches your change (e.g. `feat/thing`, `fix/thing`, `chore/thing`, `docs/thing`, `refactor/thing`, `test/thing`, `ci/thing`, `build/thing`, `perf/thing`)
2. Make all changes on that branch
3. Commit and push the branch; open a pull request
4. **After merge**: `git checkout main && git pull` — delete the merged branch locally: `git branch -d <type>/your-branch`

## No Direct Pushes to main

- Direct pushes to `main` are blocked by branch protection
- All changes to `main` must go through a PR
- PRs require at least one approval and (when configured) code owner review

## Required Checks

When branch protection and CI are configured:

- **Version check** (`.github/workflows/version-check.yml`): Validates conventional commits and comments with the version that will be released when the PR is merged.
- **Code owner review** and any other branch protection rules (see repo Settings).

## Conventional Commits and versioning

Version numbers are generated from conventional commits on merge to `main`. See the `conventional-commits-versioning` rule for commit types → version bump. Use the correct type so the release workflow produces the right version.

## Conventional Commits (summary)

Use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/) for commit messages:

- `feat:` – new feature
- `fix:` or `perf:` – bug fix or performance
- `chore:` – maintenance, dependencies
- `docs:` – documentation
- `refactor:` – code refactoring
- `test:` – tests
- `ci:` or `build:` – CI/CD or build changes

Add `!` or `BREAKING CHANGE` footer for breaking changes.

## PR Template

When present, PR descriptions follow the template (`.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md`) with:

- **what** – high-level description of changes
- **why** – rationale and business case
- **testing, docs & notes** – testing approach, docs, breaking changes, AI assistant usage
- **references** – links to issues or docs (e.g. `closes #123`)

## When Creating PRs (AI Assistants)

- Ensure the work is on a branch (not `main`) before creating a PR. If the user is on `main`, create a branch from the current state and re-apply or cherry-pick commits as needed so the PR is from a branch.
- When creating a PR (e.g. via `gh pr create`), **always output a clickable link** to the PR so the user can open it immediately. Example: `[PR #123](https://github.com/opsdevcode/cloudopt/pull/123)`.

## Branch Protection (GitHub Settings)

This repo configures branch protection for `main`:

- Require a pull request before merging
- Require approval(s) and code owner review (see CODEOWNERS)
- Do not allow force pushes or branch deletion from the UI
